        bodyHtml: `
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">Overview</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wickes and B&Q sit at the accessible end of the UK kitchen market — both DIY and home improvement retailers offering kitchen ranges aimed at homeowners with modest budgets or straightforward replacement projects. Neither competes with the design-led offering of Wren, Magnet, or Howdens, but both fill an important role for homeowners looking for a functional kitchen at a controlled cost.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Unit Format</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Both Wickes and B&Q supply kitchens in flat-pack or semi-assembled formats. Neither offers the fully pre-assembled rigid carcasses that trade suppliers like Howdens and Benchmarx — or higher-end consumer brands like Wren and Magnet — provide as standard. This means on-site assembly is required, which adds time to the installation and has implications for labour cost.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Semi-assembled units — where some components are pre-fitted at the factory — reduce on-site assembly time compared to fully flat-pack units. Check the specific range you are purchasing to understand what comes pre-assembled and what requires on-site work. This information should be available in the product specification at the point of purchase.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Range and Styles</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Wickes has a relatively focused kitchen range, concentrating on a limited number of door styles and finishes. This makes the range easy to navigate but limits customisation options for homeowners with specific aesthetic requirements. B&Q sells its kitchens under the Cooke & Lewis and GoodHome brands, offering a slightly wider selection across different price tiers.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Neither Wickes nor B&Q offers the breadth of a specialist kitchen retailer. For homeowners who know exactly what they want and need a straightforward, cost-effective solution, both can work well. For homeowners who want extensive customisation or a kitchen designed around unusual room dimensions, a specialist retailer will offer more flexibility.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Installation Complexity</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The flat-pack or semi-assembled nature of Wickes and B&Q kitchens adds complexity relative to fully pre-assembled units. However, both brands use broadly standard UK kitchen dimensions and fixings, meaning any experienced kitchen fitter should be able to install either without significant difficulty.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The main risk with budget kitchens from any source is inconsistency in component quality. Flat-pack components occasionally have minor manufacturing tolerances that require adjustment on-site. An experienced fitter will manage this; an inexperienced one may produce a less satisfying result. At the budget end of the market, the quality of the installation matters proportionally more, not less — poor fitting of cheap units is particularly visible.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Value for Money</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">On headline purchase price, both Wickes and B&Q offer competitive entry-level kitchens. However, total fitted cost — kitchen price plus installation labour — is the correct metric to use when comparing value. The additional installation time required for flat-pack units means the cost advantage of a cheaper kitchen is partially offset by higher labour costs.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">For straightforward, small-to-medium kitchens where budget is the primary constraint, Wickes and B&Q can represent good value. For larger, more complex kitchens, the total cost gap between budget flat-pack and mid-market rigid-unit kitchens narrows considerably once installation labour is included in the calculation.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Which Should You Choose?</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">If budget is your primary constraint and your kitchen is a straightforward layout without complex design requirements, either Wickes or B&Q can be a sensible choice. If you have a modest additional budget to spend, it is worth comparing the total fitted cost of a mid-range rigid-unit kitchen — the lower installation cost and better long-term durability may make the upgrade worthwhile.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Whichever brand you choose, invest in a thorough pre-installation survey. Accurate measurements and a detailed plan reduce the risk of components not fitting correctly — a risk that is amplified with flat-pack kitchens where flexibility in on-site adjustment is more limited than with bespoke or semi-bespoke rigid units.</p>
        `,
