                  <td class="px-4 py-3" style="color: var(--text-soft);">£4,000–£7,500+</td>
                  <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold" style="color: var(--teal);">£16,000–£47,500+</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p class="text-xs mb-6" style="color: var(--text-soft);">All figures are indicative ranges for Coventry and Warwickshire in 2025. Actual costs depend on kitchen size, configuration, and project-specific requirements. Installation figures exclude worktops (if separately supplied), appliances, tiling, and decoration.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">What Drives Installation Cost?</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Installation cost is driven primarily by the number of units, the complexity of the layout, and the scope of associated trades work. Key cost factors include: number of base and wall units; whether an island is included; number of appliance connections (oven, hob, dishwasher, fridge, extractor); worktop complexity (number of joints, material); and whether strip-out of an existing kitchen is required.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Unit format also affects cost — flat-pack kitchens require on-site assembly before fitting, adding time and therefore cost. Pre-assembled rigid units are faster to install and typically result in a lower installation cost per unit.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Getting an Accurate Quote</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The only reliable way to understand your total fitted cost is through a pre-installation survey. A surveyor visits your home, takes precise measurements, reviews your kitchen plan, and identifies any complications before they arise on installation day. Following the survey, a fixed-price installation quote is provided, allowing you to budget accurately for the complete project.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Install My Kitchen's pre-installation survey costs £195 and is credited back in full when you proceed with the installation. It is the single most effective way to avoid budget surprises on any kitchen project.</p>
        `,
        takeaways: [
          "Total fitted kitchen cost = kitchen price + installation. Installation typically adds £1,800–£7,500 depending on size and complexity.",
          "Flat-pack kitchens cost more to install per unit than rigid pre-assembled units — the purchase price saving is partially offset by higher labour.",
          "A pre-installation survey is the only accurate way to establish your total fitted cost before committing to a kitchen purchase.",
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "How much does kitchen installation cost in 2025?", a: "Kitchen installation in Coventry and Warwickshire typically costs £1,800–£7,500 depending on kitchen size, layout complexity, and the scope of trades work required. A pre-installation survey provides a fixed-price quote specific to your project." },
          { q: "Why does installation cost vary so much?", a: "Installation cost is driven by the number of units, layout complexity, appliance connections, worktop complexity, and whether strip-out is required. A large L-shaped kitchen with an island and five appliance connections will cost significantly more to install than a simple galley kitchen." },
          { q: "Are IKEA kitchens actually cheaper when you include installation?", a: "Not necessarily. IKEA flat-pack units require on-site assembly, which adds time and installation cost. When total fitted cost is compared — kitchen price plus installation — the gap between IKEA and mid-range rigid-unit kitchens is often smaller than headline prices suggest." },
          { q: "Does worktop cost affect installation cost?", a: "Worktop supply and installation are typically quoted separately. The complexity of the worktop — number of joints, material (laminate, solid wood, quartz, granite), and whether templating is required — adds to the overall project cost. Worktop installation is usually included in an installation quote only if explicitly confirmed." },
        ],
      },
    },

    // ── 9. Professional Fitter vs DIY ──────────────────────────────────────
    {
      params: { comparison: "kitchen-fitter-vs-diy-kitchen-installation" },
      props: {
        slug: "kitchen-fitter-vs-diy-kitchen-installation",
        title: "Professional Kitchen Fitter vs DIY — Is It Worth Hiring a Pro?",
        metaTitle: "Professional Kitchen Fitter vs DIY Installation | Install My Kitchen",
        metaDescription: "Is DIY kitchen installation worth the risk? Compare professional fitting vs DIY on quality, cost, time, safety and warranty implications for UK homeowners.",
        answer: "Professional kitchen installation ensures correct levelling, plumbing and appliance connections, avoids costly mistakes, and typically comes with a workmanship warranty. DIY is possible for experienced individuals but mistakes can be expensive to correct.",
        col1Name: "Professional Fitter",
        col2Name: "DIY",
        criteria: ["Levelling accuracy", "Plumbing & electrical", "Worktop templating", "Warranty coverage", "Risk of costly errors"],
        col1Points: ["Laser levels, professional tools", "Certified connections where required", "Professionally templated and cut", "Workmanship warranty included", "Very low with experienced fitter"],
        col2Points: ["Relies on personal skill level", "Self-certified (limitations apply)", "Risk of cutting errors", "No warranty on DIY work", "Higher risk without trade experience"],
        bodyHtml: `
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">The Appeal of DIY Kitchen Installation</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Kitchen installation is one of those projects that many confident DIYers look at and think: how hard can it be? Assemble some boxes, screw them to the wall, slot the worktop on top. For a straightforward galley kitchen with no island, no complex appliance connections, and walls that are genuinely flat, level, and plumb, a highly experienced DIYer can produce a satisfactory result.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The problem is that most UK kitchens do not have flat, level, plumb walls. Most have at least one wall that wanders, a floor that slopes, a corner that is not square. And it is precisely at these points — where experience, professional tools, and trade knowledge make the difference — that DIY kitchen installations tend to go wrong.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Levelling and Setting Out</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The first stage of any kitchen installation — establishing datum lines, setting out the layout, and determining how to handle floor and wall variations — is also the most important. Get this right and the rest of the installation follows logically. Get it wrong and every subsequent stage is compromised.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Professional fitters use laser levels as a matter of course. They understand how to handle floors that slope across their length, walls that are more or less than 90 degrees at the corners, and ceiling heights that vary across the room. Managing these variables correctly requires experience and the right tools. DIY attempts using a spirit level and a best-guess approach frequently produce results that are visibly off-level or misaligned, particularly when doors and drawers are hung.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Plumbing and Electrical Connections</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Kitchen installations involve both plumbing (sink, dishwasher, sometimes fridge or instant hot water tap) and electrical work (oven, hob, extractor, lighting, sockets). Some of this work can be carried out by a confident DIYer under current UK regulations; other work requires a qualified and Part P-registered electrician.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">In particular, new circuits and work in zones near water sources must be carried out by a competent person and, in many cases, notified to building control. A professional kitchen fitter either carries the relevant qualifications or works with qualified sub-contractors and co-ordinates the trades efficiently. A DIY installation that bypasses these requirements creates a safety risk and a liability that will need to be resolved before the property is sold.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Worktop Templating and Cutting</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Worktop templating and cutting is one of the highest-risk stages of a kitchen installation for a DIYer. Stone and engineered stone worktops (quartz, granite) must be templated and cut by specialists — there is no realistic DIY option here. Solid wood, laminate, and Corian worktops can be cut on-site, but the precision required — particularly for mitre joints in corners — demands both specialist tools and experience.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">A single poorly cut worktop joint is not only visually poor — it is also a potential ingress point for moisture that will cause the worktop to swell and delaminate over time. Worktop replacement is a significant additional cost. A professional fitter who guarantees their worktop work against defects in workmanship provides an important protection that DIY installation cannot offer.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Cost of Mistakes</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">DIY kitchen installation may save you the installation labour cost, but mistakes are expensive. A miscut worktop may need to be replaced. Units that are not correctly levelled may need to be refitted. Doors and drawers that are misaligned, hinges that are incorrectly positioned, and plinths that are poorly cut all require remedial work that, if carried out by a professional, costs more than the original installation would have done.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">The risk is not hypothetical. A significant proportion of professional kitchen fitters carry out remedial work on DIY or poorly executed installations. The cost of putting right a DIY installation that has gone wrong typically far exceeds the cost that was saved by not hiring a professional in the first place.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">When DIY Might Be Appropriate</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">There are circumstances where DIY installation is a reasonable option. If you are a tradesperson yourself — a joiner, a builder, or an experienced kitchen fitter — you may be able to install your own kitchen competently. If your kitchen is a simple, small galley layout with no island and only basic appliance connections, the complexity is lower. If you are fitting a budget kitchen and are genuinely prepared to accept a less-than-perfect result, the calculation changes.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">For the vast majority of homeowners, particularly those installing a kitchen costing £5,000 or more, professional installation is the sensible choice. The cost of installation is a small fraction of the total project cost — but the quality of the installation determines how the kitchen performs and looks for the next fifteen to twenty years.</p>
        `,
        takeaways: [
          "Professional installation ensures correct levelling, compliant electrical and plumbing connections, and accurate worktop templating — all high-risk areas for DIY.",
          "Mistakes in DIY kitchen installation are expensive to correct; remedial work typically costs more than the original installation saving.",
          "For kitchens costing £5,000 or more, professional installation is a small percentage of total project cost but determines long-term quality.",
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "Can I legally install my own kitchen in the UK?", a: "The physical fitting work (assembling and fixing units) can be done by a homeowner. However, new electrical circuits and work near water sources must meet Part P building regulations and may need to be carried out by a qualified electrician and notified to building control." },
          { q: "What tools do I need to install a kitchen myself?", a: "At minimum: a laser level, a drill, a jigsaw, a circular saw, a workbench, and a range of hand tools. Professional fitters carry specialist tools that are costly to buy for a single project, including worktop cutters, biscuit joiners for worktop joints, and fixing jigs." },
          { q: "How long does it take to install a kitchen yourself?", a: "For an experienced DIYer, a standard kitchen might take one to two weeks spread across evenings and weekends. An experienced professional fitter would complete the same kitchen in three to seven days. The difference is tools, experience, and full-time focus." },
          { q: "Does DIY kitchen installation affect my kitchen warranty?", a: "Product warranties from reputable retailers cover manufacturing defects regardless of who installs the kitchen. However, some retailers may require evidence of professional installation to honour warranty claims related to installation. Check your specific retailer's terms." },
        ],
      },
    },

    // ── 10. German vs British Kitchen Installation ─────────────────────────
    {
      params: { comparison: "german-kitchen-installation-vs-british" },
      props: {
        slug: "german-kitchen-installation-vs-british",
        title: "German Kitchen Installation vs British — What's the Difference?",
        metaTitle: "German Kitchen Installation vs British | Install My Kitchen",
        metaDescription: "German kitchens (Häcker, Nobilia, Schuller, Rotpunkt) require tighter tolerances and more precise installation than British-market kitchens. Here's what to expect.",
        answer: "German kitchens (Häcker, Nobilia, Rotpunkt, Schuller) are precision-engineered to tighter tolerances and typically require more careful installation than British-market kitchens. They demand accurate levels and walls. British kitchens (Howdens, Magnet, Wren) are designed for the UK trade and have more flexibility.",
        col1Name: "German Kitchen",
        col2Name: "British Kitchen",
        criteria: ["Manufacturing tolerances", "Wall/floor preparation required", "Installation complexity", "Time required", "Fitter experience needed"],
        col1Points: ["Very tight — 1mm or less", "Walls and floor must be true", "Higher — less on-site adjustment", "Longer — 20–30% more time typical", "Specialist German kitchen experience"],
        col2Points: ["Standard trade tolerances", "Tolerant of typical UK variation", "Standard — good scope for adjustment", "Standard installation timeline", "Experienced kitchen fitter"],
        bodyHtml: `
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">What Makes German Kitchens Different?</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">German kitchen brands — Häcker, Nobilia, Rotpunkt, Schuller, Nolte, and others — are manufactured to precision engineering standards that reflect the German approach to quality manufacturing. Units are built to tight dimensional tolerances, with consistent carcass construction and door hanging systems that operate with minimal adjustment range. This precision is a strength when walls, floors and ceilings are truly level and plumb. It becomes a challenge when they are not.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">British-market kitchens — Howdens, Magnet, Wren, and others — are designed specifically for the realities of UK housing stock: walls that wander, floors that slope, and corners that are rarely perfectly square. British kitchen systems typically have greater on-site adjustment built in, allowing fitters to compensate for room irregularities without compromising the finished appearance.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Manufacturing Tolerances</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">German kitchens are engineered to tolerances of one millimetre or less. This is impressive from a manufacturing standpoint, but it means that any deviation in the installation environment — a wall that is 2–3mm out of plumb, a floor that slopes by a few millimetres across its width — creates visible problems. Units that do not sit perfectly level produce door and drawer alignment issues that cannot be fully corrected through hinge adjustment.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">British kitchens are designed with more generous tolerances and greater adjustment range at hinges, drawer runners, and leg levellers. This gives the fitter more options to compensate for imperfect conditions without compromising the result. It does not mean British kitchens are lower quality — it means they are designed for the environment in which they are installed.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Wall and Floor Preparation</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">For a German kitchen installation to achieve the result its engineering demands, the room preparation must be thorough. Walls should be genuinely flat and plumb — not just approximately level. Floors should be levelled, either by grinding down high spots or applying a self-levelling compound. Corners should be checked for squareness and any significant deviation addressed before installation begins.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">This preparation stage is sometimes skipped or underestimated, particularly when a homeowner is managing the project themselves. The consequences of installing a German kitchen in a room that has not been properly prepared are visible — doors that run at a slight angle, gaps at the tops of tall units, and handles that are not perfectly aligned. Correcting these issues after installation is difficult and expensive.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Installation Complexity and Time</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">German kitchen installation typically takes 20–30% longer than an equivalent British kitchen installation. The additional time goes on more careful setting out, more precise levelling, and more meticulous alignment of components. German kitchen systems often use proprietary fixing methods and hardware that differ from standard UK kitchen fittings — fitters without specific German kitchen experience can struggle with these differences.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Choosing a fitter with documented experience of the specific brand you are installing is particularly important with German kitchens. A Häcker kitchen, for example, uses a specific wall hanging system and carcass construction that an experienced Häcker fitter will navigate efficiently. A fitter who has only ever installed Wren and Howdens may be technically capable but will work more slowly and may encounter problems that experience would have anticipated.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Cost Implications</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">German kitchen installation costs more than equivalent British kitchen installation, reflecting the additional time, the level of preparation required, and the specialist experience needed. Installation for a German kitchen in the Coventry and Warwickshire area typically starts from £4,000 and can reach £7,500 or more for large, complex installations. This is broadly 20–40% higher than equivalent British kitchen installation, depending on complexity and preparation requirements.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Given that German kitchens typically represent a significant investment — often £12,000–£40,000 or more — the additional installation cost is proportionally small. Attempting to save money on installation by using a fitter without specific German kitchen experience is a false economy that risks a result that does not reflect the quality of the product.</p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4 mt-8" style="color: var(--navy);">Which Is Right for You?</h2>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">German kitchens are engineered to a very high standard and, when installed correctly in a properly prepared room, produce a precision result that justifies the premium. British kitchens are designed for the realities of UK housing stock and deliver excellent results in a wider range of conditions. Neither is inherently superior — the right choice depends on your budget, your aesthetic requirements, and the condition of your room.</p>
          <p class="mb-4" style="color: var(--text-soft);">Whatever you choose, invest in a pre-installation survey. For a German kitchen in particular, the survey is essential — it identifies any room preparation required before installation, confirms the plan against actual room dimensions, and ensures your fitter arrives on installation day with a complete understanding of the job ahead.</p>
        `,
        takeaways: [
          "German kitchens are engineered to tighter tolerances than British-market kitchens — room preparation (level walls, true floors) is essential before installation.",
          "German kitchen installation typically takes 20–30% longer and costs 20–40% more than an equivalent British kitchen installation.",
          "Always use a fitter with specific experience of the German kitchen brand you are installing — proprietary fixing systems vary significantly between brands.",
        ],
        faqs: [
          { q: "Do German kitchens need special fitters?", a: "Yes. German kitchens use proprietary fixing systems and have tighter engineering tolerances than British-market kitchens. A fitter with specific experience of your brand — Häcker, Nobilia, Schuller, Rotpunkt, or others — will produce a significantly better result than one without this experience." },
          { q: "Does my room need to be specially prepared for a German kitchen?", a: "More so than for a British kitchen, yes. Walls should be flat and plumb, floors level, and corners checked for squareness. A pre-installation survey will identify any preparation required and is particularly important for German kitchen projects." },
          { q: "Why does German kitchen installation cost more?", a: "German kitchen installation takes longer due to tighter tolerances, more careful setting out, and specialist handling of proprietary fixing systems. The installation cost reflects this additional time and the experience required." },
          { q: "Can any kitchen fitter install a German kitchen?", a: "Technically yes, but practically speaking a fitter without specific German kitchen experience will work more slowly, may encounter problems that an experienced fitter would anticipate, and is more likely to produce alignment issues that cannot be fully corrected after installation." },
        ],
      },
    },
  ];
}

// ── Page rendering ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

const {
  slug,
  title,
  metaTitle,
  metaDescription,
  answer,
  col1Name,
  col2Name,
  criteria,
  col1Points,
  col2Points,
  bodyHtml,
  takeaways,
  faqs,
} = Astro.props;

const canonical = `https://www.installmykitchen.co.uk/comparisons/${slug}/`;

// Truncate display title to ≤65 chars for <title>
const displayTitle = metaTitle.length <= 65 ? metaTitle : metaTitle.substring(0, 62) + "...";

const internalLinks = [
  { label: "Kitchen Installation Costs", href: "/costs/", description: "Detailed cost breakdown for Coventry & Warwickshire" },
  { label: "Pre-Installation Survey", href: "/survey/", description: "How our £195 survey saves you money" },
  { label: "Retailers We Install", href: "/retailers/", description: "Every major UK kitchen retailer covered" },
  { label: "Our Services", href: "/services/", description: "Full scope of kitchen installation services" },
];

// BreadcrumbList JSON-LD
const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  itemListElement: [
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 1, name: "Home", item: "https://www.installmykitchen.co.uk/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 2, name: "Comparisons", item: "https://www.installmykitchen.co.uk/comparisons/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", position: 3, name: title, item: canonical },
  ],
};
---

<Base
  title={displayTitle}
  description={metaDescription}
  canonical={canonical}
>
  <script slot="schema" type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />

  <Header slot="header" />

  <!-- Page header -->
  <section class="page-header" aria-label="Page header">
    <div class="container">
      <Breadcrumbs
        items={[
          { label: "Comparisons", href: "/comparisons/" },
          { label: title, href: `/comparisons/${slug}/` },
        ]}
      />
      <h1 class="page-h1">{title}</h1>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Main content -->
  <section class="section" style="background: #fff;">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="max-w-3xl">

        <!-- Quick answer -->
        <AnswerBlock answer={answer} />

        <!-- Comparison table -->
        {criteria && criteria.length > 0 && (
          <div class="comparison-table-wrap my-8 fade-up">
            <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4" style="color: var(--navy);">At a Glance</h2>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border" style="border-color: var(--border);">
              <table class="w-full border-collapse text-sm">
                <thead>
                  <tr style="background: var(--navy); color: #fff;">
                    <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold w-1/3">Feature</th>
                    <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold w-1/3">{col1Name}</th>
                    <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold w-1/3">{col2Name}</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  {criteria.map((criterion: string, i: number) => (
                    <tr
                      class="border-b"
                      style={`border-color: var(--border); ${i % 2 === 1 ? "background: var(--bg-light);" : ""}`}
                    >
                      <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium" style="color: var(--charcoal);">{criterion}</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3" style="color: var(--text-soft);">{col1Points[i] ?? "—"}</td>
                      <td class="px-4 py-3" style="color: var(--text-soft);">{col2Points[i] ?? "—"}</td>
                    </tr>
                  ))}
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>
        )}

        <!-- Body content -->
        <div class="body-content fade-up" set:html={bodyHtml} />

        <!-- Key Takeaways -->
        <div class="mt-8 fade-up">
          <KeyTakeaway points={takeaways} />
        </div>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section class="mt-10 fade-up" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
          <h2 id="faq-heading" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-6" style="color: var(--navy);">
            Frequently Asked Questions
          </h2>
          <FAQ items={faqs} schemaId={`faq-comparison-${slug}`} />
        </section>

        <!-- Internal Links -->
        <div class="mt-10 fade-up">
          <InternalLinks links={internalLinks} heading="Related Pages" />
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <CTA
    dark={true}
    heading="Ready to Book Your Kitchen Installation Survey?"
    subtext="A pre-installation survey gives you a fixed-price quote before you commit. £195, credited back in full when you proceed."
    primaryLabel="Book Your Survey — £195"
    primaryHref="/survey/"
    secondaryLabel="Call 07399 651836"
    secondaryHref="tel:07399651836"
  />

  <Footer slot="footer" />
  <StickyMobileCTA slot="sticky-cta" />
</Base>

<style>
  .page-header {
    background: var(--hero-gradient);
    padding: 3rem 0 3.5rem;
  }

  .page-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(1.5rem, 2.75vw, 2.25rem);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: #fff;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    max-width: 720px;
  }

  .body-content {
    line-height: 1.75;
  }

  .body-content p {
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
</style>
